MD5 is a cryptographic hash function that takes an input of any size and produces a 128-bit hash value. It is used to verify the integrity of data and to detect tampering.

To get the MD5 check sum of a file using Java, you can use the following code:

```java
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.io.*;
import java.security.MessageDigest;

public class MD5Checksum {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("input.txt");
        MessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance("MD5");
        byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
        int bytesRead = 0;
        while ((bytesRead = fis.read(buffer))!= -1) {
            md.update(buffer, 0, bytesRead);
        }
        fis.close();
        String hash = new String(Base64.encodeBase64(md.digest()));
        System.out.println("MD5 checksum of input.txt is " + hash);
    }
}
```

This code will read the contents of the input.txt file and calculate the MD5 checksum. The output will be the MD5 checksum in base64 encoding.

